comment.author: 30682253@N00
comment._content:
I note the comments assuming that these are aviary birds.

There used to be 5 and sometimes 7 kookaburras line up exactly like this at our home in Stirling in the Adelaide Hills, just 5 years ago.

They were "wild" in so far as birds which are fed by the locals can be.

It took almost 2 years for them to learn that we would not feed tham and by our 4th year there they were notpresent like this, only a single pair and occasional young.

While there were so many Kookaburras we did not see small birds such as blue wrens and grey shrike thrushes.
We watched the kookaburras steal the nestlings from the Grey shrike thrushes nests 2 years in a row.


Trying to educate people NOT to fee free birds (no longer "wild" imo, is a real task.
:(
